##"There's always a need for new coronaviruses. Humans can't be chased by viruses. "

Lifeweek

Features an introduction to a magazine and the life he advocates.

On January 26, the Virus Institute of the Chinese Center for Disease Control and Prevention said it had successfully isolated the new coronavirus and was screening seed strains. The screening of seed strains is the first step in developing a vaccine, and more than a dozen institutions across the country are pushing ahead with the development of a new Split Second based vaccine.
The researchers interviewed said the new vaccine would be a race against time. Even if the virus can not catch up with the speed, new crown vaccine development is always necessary, at least to prepare for the next possible epidemic, "human beings can not always be caught up in an outbreak of infectious disease. "

By Yan Yan

From SARS vaccine to new Crown Vaccine

On January 10th Zhang Linqi, a professor at Tsinghua University's School of Medicine, got the genome sequence of the new coronavirus, and a dozen or so people began working on it on a continuous basis, each of them well aware of the prospect of a vaccine called the Golden Cap, it's a race against time. The lab had a strict schedule, which experiments had to be done the same day, and which could wait a little bit, "people who were working on the SARS vaccine are now working on the new crown vaccine. ".

Over the years, Zhang's team has pushed ahead with research on a vaccine for the coronavirus. In the case of Mers (Middle East Respiratory Syndrome virus) in particular, his team has completed animal-level trials of the MERS vaccine, which was validated but then stalled without more funding.

Expedition photography

According to statistics, there were more than a dozen institutions that did vaccine research and development during SARS, but after the release of the virus genome, it took researchers 20 months to move into human clinical trials, long after the SARS epidemic had disappeared, the vaccine market plan because of the difficulties of clinical advancement, follow-up funding shortage, on this hold.

"I'm really sorry. If we can get a SARS vaccine this time, at least we can get some protection against the new crown. Since both SARS and the new coronavirus share a receptor protein, ACE2, if the SARS vaccine provides a protective immune response to humans, it could, to some extent, block the entry of the new coronavirus. Zhang said. Now, in addition to understanding the commonalities between the new coronavirus and the SARS virus, Zhang's team is constantly examining the differences in structure and function.

In fact, on February 5th the British government added another 20m pounds (40m pounds in total) to the research and development of a new crown vaccine and vaccine technology. The research initiated by the Department of Health in 2019-nCov Rapid Response Call Application explicitly mentions the concept of "Cross-reactivity" , which is the use of different subtypes of viruses for virus protection tests in vaccine efficacy evaluation, to test the protective rate of the vaccine. Zhang Linqi explained that, "What the UK government is looking for is an existing vaccine candidate with cross-protection against the new coronavirus. This means that if front-line health care workers are vaccinated against SARS, there is a possibility of reducing health care infections in this outbreak, " he said.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
"We all know it takes a long time to develop a vaccine, but from what we used to know about viruses like SARS, I can pat myself on the chest and say, this vaccine is going to work! But to respect the laws of nature, it requires step-by-step experimentation." Takatomi, director of the CDC, said.

In fact, vaccine development is divided into three major parts: seed strain screening and reagents, animal models of cross-protection tests, and clinical trials to verify the safety and efficacy. On Jan. 26, Xu Wenbo, director of the COVID-19, said the center had started research and development of a vaccine, had successfully isolated the virus and was screening seed strains.

After screening the strain, which model to choose to develop the vaccine is also an important factor affecting the success of vaccine development. Zhang Linqi said, "Now each agency has chosen a different strategy for Vaccine Development, and we are comparing and testing each other as we work together to find the most effective vaccine. But it's a combination of resources, capabilities, and technology to figure out what the vaccine strategy is going to be.

The good news is that the new crown vaccine may not be that difficult to develop. Zhang explained that many people have the experience of getting an annual flu vaccine, which they need to get every year because the flu virus has such a high mutation rate that it uses mutations to escape the immune system. By contrast, the new coronavirus so far does not appear to have much variation. "from respiratory samples from patients in Wuhan, Beijing and even the United States, the genetic sequences of all strains are almost identical. To some extent, this supports the conclusion that the mutation rate of new coronavirus is not high. At the very least, the virus has so far not undergone any genetic mutations, which we suspect may be simpler than the development of a flu vaccine.".

As for the new Crown Vaccine Research and development time, Zhang Linqi said it is impossible to predict. "Personally, I think all the reports that have been made so far have been too quick to estimate the time of the vaccine. The safety of prophylactic vaccines is paramount, and safety trials take at least six months to complete, while evaluation of their effectiveness requires testing live viruses in animals, and accurate data can not be obtained in a month or two. These are extraordinary times, but they can not be crossed.".

Is Not a vaccine that can be predicted regularly

"The fastest way to get a working vaccine out of a strain today is with a flu vaccine, such as the one that went around last year, and we predict that it can be used to prevent this year's flu, so take it out and make a vaccine for everyone. ". Feng Yong, an associate professor of pathogenic biology at the Wuhan University, said in a previous interview.

Vaccine Development is always in a race with the virus to mutate, so why do people get flu shots every year in time?

In some ways, because flu is "seasonal, " meaning it comes every year, vaccines can be developed in advance to combat the vagaries of the flu virus. In addition, the influenza vaccine preparation process has a relatively complete set of prediction mechanism.

Li Shuming, who has worked for years on the pathogenesis of Influenza Viruses and vaccines, was interviewed for this magazine. He explained to this magazine that, "The Harbin Institute of Veterinary Medicine and the University of Hong Kong's two national influenza virus epidemic surveillance centers take quarterly samples for observation. They report to the National Center for Disease Control and Prevention and the Health Commission, and integrate who reporting guidelines to update the epidemic reports of the strains and finally identify the major epidemic strains. So a flu vaccine is never the vaccine of the season, it's predicted and then made in advance."

So, will the new crown vaccine also have such a prediction mechanism?

The idea is that the new coronavirus could become an epidemic in the future, perhaps even like the flu. John  Johan Nichols, a clinical professor of pathology at the University of Hong Kong, recently said, "my feeling is that the new crown will be like SARS. In about five months, people basically have a very bad cold. ".

But Li Shaoming is against it, "I don't think the new crown will evolve into a flu-like infection. Although the influenza virus and the new coronavirus are RNA viruses, are transmitted through the respiratory tract, the early symptoms are very similar, clinically easy to cause confusion, difficult to distinguish diagnosis. But the most fundamental difference between the new crown and the flu virus is that there is no valid evidence that patients with the new crown can heal themselves and do not cause recoverable damage to the lungs or other organs. Even if most patients have mild disease, it doesn't mean their lungs don't leave an imaging trail. In addition, influenza virus mainly causes fever, cough, runny nose, rare pneumonia and moderate or severe pneumonia in clinic, while new crown infection mainly causes lung disease, most patients with mild or moderate or severe pneumonia.

Li is more likely to think that, like SARS, the human-to-human transmission of the new crown will be eliminated. "humans are not the natural host of the virus, and from an epidemiological point of view, the virus lacks the basis for an effective long-term epidemic. Although several asymptomatic infections have been reported in the media, they have yet to be proven medically. Based on this, it would be a mistake to think the disease would be as good as the flu.".

Because the new coronavirus is a sudden infectious disease, it is not suitable for influenza vaccine prediction mechanism. "since SARS has not occurred in humans since then, there is no way to do epidemiological surveillance, " Li added. "The current information about the virus can only come from patients infected with the epidemic. After the epidemic is over, it is very likely that new information about the virus can not be detected and the corresponding strategy for Vaccine Prevention and control can not be made. ".

So, if the new crown eventually disappears, as SARS did, is vaccine development necessary?

Can't keep getting chased by a virus

"every time an acute infectious disease breaks out, people are so passive that they can not catch up with the spread of the virus. If a vaccine can be developed ahead of time, it is equivalent to putting a gun in the gun and waiting for the virus to appear and annihilate it directly, " Zhang said. The Bill Gates also said in a 2015 public address: "When I was a kid, our biggest concern was nuclear war, but if something could kill tens of millions of people in the future, it would probably be a highly contagious virus, not war. We are spending a lot of money on nuclear deterrence, but very little on pandemic preparedness."

"In fact, people should be prepared for infectious diseases, but infectious diseases come infrequently and by accident, profit-oriented enterprises will not be willing to invest to do it, while other relevant departments may be limited by vision and wisdom, and there is no awareness of reserve in advance. ". Zhang Linqi said helplessly.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Zhang has been advocating for years for a joint government research facility to establish a mechanism for sudden outbreaks of acute infectious diseases. "build up the technology for the vaccine in advance. For example, the development of a vaccine in some institutions has completed Phase I clinical trials to verify the safety of the vaccine, to Phase II clinical, this time may be directly applied to the prevention and control of the epidemic. In order to test the safety and efficacy of vaccines, Phase I clinical trials of vaccines are conducted on a small scale in healthy people; Phase II clinical trials of preventive vaccines are generally conducted in high-risk populations, where the presence of an epidemic is required to verify the efficacy of a vaccine; and Phase III clinical trials are generally conducted in large populations (including high-risk and healthy populations) to further verify the efficacy of a vaccine. This part of the research work also needs to be carried out in the context of an epidemic situation, which means that once the epidemic is over there is no infected person and there is no way to test the efficacy of a vaccine.".

This initiative can also be found in the international public organization "Epidemic Prevention Innovation Alliance" (CEPI) in the corresponding concept. It follows a # 20m donation from the UK government. In addition, the Gates Foundation has spent $60 million on vaccines and treatments for the new coronavirus, including CEPI. "There is nothing wrong with China's vaccine production capacity at this stage, but sometimes it is not the technology but the wisdom to prevent a sudden outbreak of infectious disease. If Phase I clinical trials of the vaccine are completed, the country will use it as a technical reserve for public projects in case of emergency, and push on to Phase II clinical trials as soon as it is needed, vaccine development will be more effective.". Zhang said.

An industry insider, who asked not to be named, told this newspaper, "The US has two forces at work on this. One is the National Institutes of Health, which does research on all kinds of infectious diseases, and they have a technology base, but they don't necessarily produce a vaccine. The other is the large biopharmaceutical enterprises, based on the market interest drive, will have the selective input resources production reserve. It's important to note that vaccines are a public good in the United States, and the government will spend a lot of money to pay for it, and the industry has no qualms about it. However, in China, at least in scientific research, some severe infectious diseases are restricted by the law of major infectious diseases, and some severe infectious diseases can only be monopolized by a few qualified research institutions. The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention at all levels control the resources for vaccines in addition to carrying out prevention and control campaigns at their level.".

The story of Zaire Ebolavirus can be seen as a warning. Richard Preston wrote about the rise of the Zaire ebolavirus from 1967 to 1993 in a book called the blood plague, "We can not wait for an outbreak to start, but we can prepare in advance. HIV, Ebola, and other high risk viruses appear to have invaded previously undisturbed environments, wiping out their reservoir hosts, and so the virus needs a new one: humans. The Zaire Ebolavirus has now retreated to the depths of the jungle, where it can learn and mutate. Believe me, this monster will come back. We need to be ready."In fact, the Zaire ebolavirus returned in 2018, sweeping across eastern Congo and continuing to this day. Fortunately, on November 13,2019, Merck's Ebola vaccine went on sale, and hundreds of thousands of people have been vaccinated there and in neighboring countries since last August, effectively stopping the spread of the disease.

(Li Shaoming is an alias.)
